A083006.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{j=0..k-1} Bernoulli(j)*binomial(k,j)^2 is an integer.

A083007.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 3^k*B(k)*C(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number and C(n,k)=binomial(n,k).
formula: a(n) = 3^n * ( B(n,1/3) - B(n,0) ), where B(n,x) denotes the n-th Bernoulli polynomial. More generally, Almkvist and Meurman show that k^n * ( B(n, 1/k) - B(n, 0) ) is an integer sequence for k = 2,3,4,..., which proves the integrality of A083008 through A083014.
a(0) = 1 and for n >= 1, a(n) = 1 - 1/(n + 1)*Sum_{k = 1..n-1} 3^(n-k)*binomial(n+1,k)*a(k) (Sury, Section 1). (End)

A083008.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 4^k*B(k)*C(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number and C(n,k) = binomial(n,k).

A083009.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0,n-1} 5^k*B(k)*binomial(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number.

A083010.name: a(n) = 6^n(B_n(1/6)-B_n(0)) where B_n(x) is the n-th Bernoulli polynomial.

A083011.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 7^k*B(k)*binomial(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number.

A083012.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 8^k*B(k)*binomial(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number.

A083013.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 9^k*B(k)*binomial(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number.

A083014.name: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n-1} 10^k*B(k)*binomial(n,k) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number.

A083015.name: a(n) = the number of ordered pairs of n-bit bit strings, such that both bit strings have at least n/2 one-bits, or both have at most n/2 one-bits.
formula: a(n) = 4^n/2 + 2^n*c - c^2/2; where c is (n choose n/2) for even n, 0 for odd n.

formula: a(n) = a(n-7) + 12 for n > 7. - _Jianing Song_, Sep 22 2018

A083034.name: Numbers that are congruent to {0, 1, 3, 5, 7, 8, 10} mod 12.
formula: a(n) = a(n-7) + 12 for n > 7. - _Jianing Song_, Sep 22 2018

A083035.name: a(n) = floor(sqrt(2)*n)-2*floor(n/sqrt(2)).
formula: a(n) = floor(n*sqrt(2)) mod 2. - _T. D. Noe_, Oct 11 2006

A083037.name: a(n)=2*A083036(n)-n. Also -A123737(n).
formula: O'Bryant, Reznick, & Serbinowska show that |a(n)| <= k log n + 1, with k = 1/(2 log (1 + sqrt(2))), and further a(n) > k log n + 0.78 infinitely often. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Feb 07 2013

A083039.name: Number of divisors of n that are <= 3.

A083040.name: Number of divisors of n that are <= 4

A083043.name: Integers y such that 11*x^2 - 9*y^2 = 2 for some integer x.
formula: E.g.f.: 1 + (1/3)*exp(10*x)*(-3*cosh(3*sqrt(11)*x) + sqrt(11)*sinh(3*sqrt(11)*x)). - _Stefano Spezia_, Dec 06 2019 after _G. C. Greubel_

A083044.name: Square table read by antidiagonals forms a permutation of the natural numbers: T(n,0) = floor(n*x/(x-1))+1, T(n,k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n,k)), where x=3/2, n >= 0, k >= 0.
formula: T(A163491(n)-1, A087088(n)-1) = n. - _Peter Munn_, Jul 16 2020 [corrected _Peter Munn_, Aug 02 2020]

A083045.name: Main diagonal of table A083044.
formula: a(n) = T(n, n), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n >= 0, k >= 0, with x=3/2.

A083046.name: Antidiagonal sums of table A083044.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(k, n-k), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1))+1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n>=0, k>=0, with x=3/2.

A083047.name: Square table read by antidiagonals forms a permutation of the natural numbers: T(n,0) = floor(n*x/(x-1))+1, T(n,k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n,k)), where x = (sqrt(5)+1)/2, n>=0, k>=0.

A083048.name: Main diagonal of table A083047.
formula: a(n) = T(n, n), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n >= 0, k >= 0, with x = (sqrt(5)+1)/2.

A083049.name: Antidiagonal sums of table A083047.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(k, n-k), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1))+1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n>=0, k>=0, with x = (sqrt(5)+1)/2.

A083050.name: Square table read by antidiagonals forms a permutation of the natural numbers: T(n,0) = floor(n*x/(x-1))+1, T(n,k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n,k)), where x = sqrt(2), n>=0, k>=0.

A083052.name: Main diagonal of table A083050.
formula: a(n) = T(n, n), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n >= 0, k >= 0, with x=sqrt(2).

A083053.name: Antidiagonal sums of table A083050.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(k,n-k), where T(n,0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n,k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n,k)), for n>=0, k>=0, with x = sqrt(2).

A083054.name: a(n) = floor(sqrt(3)*n) - 3*floor(n/sqrt(3)).
formula: a(n) = floor(n*sqrt(3)) mod 3. - _T. D. Noe_, Oct 11 2006

A083055.name: a(n) = cardinality{ k<=n / A083054(k)=1}.
formula: a(n) = n/3 + O(n) (it seems O(n) could be replaced with O(log(n))).

A083058.name: Number of eigenvalues equal to 1 of n X n matrix A(i,j)=1 if j=1 or i divides j.
formula: a(1)=1, else a(n)=b(n) with b(0)=0, b(2n)=b(n)+n-1, b(2n+1)=b(n)+n. - _Ralf Stephan_, Oct 11 2003
Except for a(1), a(n) = n - 1 - floor(log(2,n)). - _Robert G. Wilson v_, Apr 19 2006
It seems that a(n) = A182220(n+1)-1 for all n>1. - _Antti Karttunen_, Aug 17 2013

A083059.name: a(n) is the number of natural numbers k such that A078496(k)=n.

A083060.name: a(n) is the number of natural numbers k such that A078496(k) = prime(n), where prime(n) denotes the n-th prime.
formula: For n > 2, a(n) = card({k: k > 3; A078496(k) = prime(n)}).

A083061.name: Triangle of coefficients of a companion polynomial to the Gandhi polynomial.
formula: Let T(i, x)=(2x+1)(x+1)T(i-1, x+1)-2x^2T(i-1, x), T(0, x)=1; so that T(1, x)=1+3x; T(2, x)=4+15x+15x^2; T(3, x)=34+147x+210x^2+105x^3, etc. Then the (i, j)-th entry in the table is the coefficient of x^j in T(i, x).
a(n, k)*2^(n-k) = A085734(n, k). - _Philippe Deléham_, Feb 27 2005

A083064.name: Square number array T(n,k)=(k(k+2)^n+1)/(k+1) read by antidiagonals.

A083065.name: 4th row of number array A083064.
formula: a(n) = 5*a(n-1)-1 with n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010

A083066.name: 5th row of number array A083064.
formula: a(n) = 6*a(n-1)-1 with n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010
a(n) = 6^n - sum(6^i, i=0..n-1) for n>0. [_Bruno Berselli_, Jun 20 2013]

A083067.name: 6th row of number array A083064.

A083068.name: 7th row of number array A083064.
formula: a(n) = 8*a(n-1)-1 with n>0, a(0)=1. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Aug 08 2010
a(n) = 8^n - sum(8^i, i=0..n-1) for n>0. - _Bruno Berselli_, Jun 20 2013

A083090.name: Main diagonal of table A083087.
formula: a(n) = T(n, n), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n >= 0, k >= 0, where x = 1+sqrt(2).

A083091.name: Antidiagonal sums of table A083087.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=0..n} T(k, n-k), where T(n, 0) = floor(n*x/(x-1)) + 1, T(n, k+1) = ceiling(x*T(n, k)), for n>=0, k>=0, with x = 1 + sqrt(2).

A083092.name: Numbers n such that 7*5^n + 2 is a prime.

A083093.name: Triangle formed by reading Pascal's triangle (A007318) mod 3.
formula: T(n,k) = Product_{i>=0} binomial(n_i,k_i) (mod 3), where n = Sum_{i>=0} n_i*3^i and k = Sum_{i>=0} k_i*3^i, 0<=n_i, k_i <=2 [Allouche et al.]. - _R. J. Mathar_, Jul 26 2017

A083094.name: Numbers k such that Sum_{j=0..k} (binomial(k,j) mod 3) is odd.

A083095.name: a(n) = A083094(n)/4.
formula: Numbers n such that C(4n, 2n) == 1 (mod 3). - _Benoit Cloitre_, Jul 30 2003

A083096.name: Numbers n such that 3 divides sum(k=1,n, C(2k,k) ).
formula: It appears that sequence gives n such that the coefficient of x^n equals 1 in prod (k>=1, 1-x^(3^k))

A083098.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 6*a(n-2).
formula: If p[1]=1, and p[i]=7, (i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n) = det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010
G.f.: G(0)/2, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(7*k-1)/(x*(7*k+6) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013

A083099.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 6*a(n-2), a(0) = 0, a(1) = 1.
formula: Simplified formula: a(n) = ((1 + sqrt(7))^n - (1 - sqrt(7))^n)/sqrt(28). - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), Jan 05 2009
G.f.: G(0)*x/(2*(1-x)), where G(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(7*k-1)/(x*(7*k+6) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 26 2013

A083100.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 7*a(n-2).
formula: a(n) = binomial transform of 1,8,8,64,64,512. - Al Hakanson (hawkuu(AT)gmail.com), Aug 17 2009

If p[1]=1, and p[i]=8,(i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010
G.f.: G(0)/(2*x) - 1/x, where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(8*k-1)/(x*(8*k+7) - 1/G(k+1))); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, May 28 2013

A083101.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 10*a(n-2).
formula: If p[1]=1, and p[i]=11, (i>1), and if A is Hessenberg matrix of order n defined by: A[i,j]=p[j-i+1], (i<=j), A[i,j]=-1, (i=j+1), and A[i,j]=0 otherwise. Then, for n>=1, a(n-1)=det A. - _Milan Janjic_, Apr 29 2010

A083102.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 10*a(n-2).
formula: G.f.: G(0)/(2-2*x), where G(k)= 1 + 1/(1 - x*(11*k-1)/( x*(11*k+10) - 1/G(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Aug 14 2013
G.f.: Q(0)/2 , where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(4*k+2 + 10*x )/( x*(4*k+4 + 10*x ) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 21 2013

A083103.name: Second-order linear recurrence sequence with a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2).

A083104.name: Second-order linear recurrence sequence with a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2).

A083114.name: Numbers with nonzero digits whose sum of digits as well as product of digits is a palindrome.

A083116.name: Smallest multiple of n using a single digit with multiplicity, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083117.name: Smallest k such that k*n contains a single digit with multiplicity, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083118.name: Index of zeros in A083116 and A083117.

A083119.name: Sum of n terms from the n-th term is a square: a(1), a(2) + a(3), a(3) + a(4) + a(5),..., a(n) + a(n+1) + ...+ a(2n-1) are squares.

A083120.name: Numbers that are congruent to {0, 2, 4, 5, 7, 9, 10} mod 12.
formula: a(n) = a(n-7) + 12 for n > 7. - _Jianing Song_, Sep 22 2018

A083121.name: Bases of the squares arising in A083119.

A083122.name: a(1) = 1, then the smallest number not included earlier and not a string of 1's such that the concatenation a(n), a(n+1) is a palindrome.

A083123.name: Smallest n-digit palindromic multiple of n, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083125.name: a(1) = 1, then the smallest number not occurring earlier such that the product of a pair of successive terms is a palindrome.

A083126.name: Palindromes arising in A083125. a(n) = A083125(n)*A083125(n+1).

A083129.name: Consider the triangle in which n-th row contains the smallest set of n consecutive numbers such that every prime among first n primes divides at least one distinct number in the row (irrespective of order). Sequence gives the first column.

A083130.name: Consider triangle in which n-th row contains the smallest set of n consecutive numbers whose LCM is divisible by primorial(n) (the product of first n primes). Sequence contains the first column.

A083131.name: Number the letters of English alphabet from 1 to 26; sequence specifies capital letters with left-right symmetry.

A083132.name: Number the letters of English alphabet from 1 to 26; sequence specifies capital letters with up-down symmetry.

A083133.name: Number the letters of English alphabet from 1 to 26; sequence specifies capital letters with no symmetry.

A083134.name: Number the letters of English alphabet from 1 to 26; sequence specifies capital letters which are indistinguishable after 180 degree rotation.

A083135.name: LCM of the terms of the n-th row of the triangle pertaining to A083130.

A083136.name: a(n+1) is the smallest palindrome greater than a(n) and relatively prime to a(n).

A083137.name: Smallest palindromic number relatively prime to all the previous terms.

A083140.name: Sieve of Eratosthenes arranged as an array and read by antidiagonals in the up direction; n-th row has property that smallest prime factor is prime(n).

A083141.name: Main diagonal of array in A083140.

A083142.name: Palindromes that cannot be expressed as the difference of two palindromes.

A083143.name: Smallest n-digit palindromic multiple of prime(n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A083144.name: Smallest k such that k*prime(n) is an n-digit palindrome, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083145.name: Smallest nontrivial palindromic multiple of the n-th palindrome (a(n) is not equal to n).

A083146.name: Smallest palindromic multiple of n-th palindrome which is not a concatenation of copies of that palindrome.

A083147.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = smallest nontrivial palindromic multiple of a(n-1). a(n) is not equal to a(n-1) or a concatenation of a(n-1) with itself.

A083149.name: a(1) = 3, a(n) = smallest nontrivial palindromic multiple of a(n-1). a(n) is not equal to a(n-1) or a concatenation of a(n-1) with itself.

A083151.name: a(1) = 5, a(n) = smallest nontrivial palindromic multiple of a(n-1). a(n) is not equal to a(n-1) or a concatenation of a(n-1) with itself.

A083158.name: Palindromes which are the arithmetic mean of two distinct palindromes.

A083159.name: Palindromes n such that the n*m is also a palindrome, where m is the next palindrome after n.

A083160.name: Palindromes n such that the n + m is also a palindrome, where m is the next palindrome after n.

A083161.name: a(n) = (concatenation of the first n terms of A099552)/n.

A083162.name: a(n) is the smallest unused proper divisor or proper multiple of n such that a(n)/n != a(m)/m for all m < n.
formula: a(a(n)) = n; a(n) = (b(k)/(k + 1)) if n = b(k) for some k and a(n) = n*(n - max{k: b(k) < n} + 1) otherwise, where b(k) is the k-th number at which a(n) < n. (Equivalently, b(k) is the unique x for which a(x)/x = (k+1).) - Carl B. Carlson (carlsonc(AT)stolaf.edu), Jan 09 2005

A083163.name: Define a function f(k) by f(k) = (k*a*b*c...)/{d*e*f...), where a,b,c,...are those nonzero digits of k which do not divide k and d,e,f,... are those nonzero digits of k which divide k. a(n) = Floor[f(k)].

A083164.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that n divides sum of the terms with index which are the divisors of n.

A083165.name: a(n) = (Sum of the terms of A083164 with index which are the divisors of n ) /n.

A083166.name: Index of terms in A083164 which are not dislocated in the rearrangement. Or k such that A083164(k) = k.

A083167.name: Triangle read by rows in which from the second row onwards the n-th row contains n smallest multiples of (n-1) not included earlier such that the row sum is a multiple of n. Triangle begins with 1.

A083171.name: a(n) = the arithmetic mean of the n-th row of triangle A083167.

A083172.name: Triangle read by rows: T(1, 1) = 1 and for n > 1, T(n, k) = A083167(n, k)/(n-1).

A083173.name: Triangle read by rows: the n-th row contains the first n-1 multiples of prime(n) followed by the next multiple that will make the row sum a multiple of n.

A083176.name: Arithmetic means of rows of A083173.

A083177.name: Let P(k) = floor(k/2). Start with n, apply P repeatedly until reach 1. a(n) = concatenation of numbers obtained.
formula: Let P(k) = floor(k/2). Start with n, apply P repeatedly until reaching 0. a(n) = concatenation of the differences of the successive numbers obtained. - _David Wasserman_, Oct 25 2004

A083178.name: Numbers with a digit sum of n and a maximum product of digits. In case of two identical products choose the largest number.
formula: Conjecture: a(n) = 10*a(n-3)+a(n-6)-10*a(n-9) for n>10. - _Colin Barker_, Oct 14 2014

For n > 7, a(n) = 11*a(n-3)-10*a(n-6). For n > 4, a(n-3) + 3*10^(floor((n-1)/3)). For n > 1, (2*10^(floor((n+2)/3))+(63*m^2-129*m-2))/6, where m is the least nonnegative residue of n mod 3. - _Chai Wah Wu_, Dec 11 2015

A083179.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest positive integer not included earlier such that the partial sums of a(A000040) are prime and the partial sums of a(A002808) are composite.

A083180.name: Numbers which retain their natural position under the rearrangement of A083179.

A083181.name: a(1)=1, a(n) = smallest positive integer not included earlier such that the partial sums of a(A000040) are composite and the partial sums of a(A002808) are primes.

A083183.name: Smallest palindromic prime using only prime digits (2,3,5,7) and having a sum of digits = prime(n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A083184.name: Smallest palindromic prime having a sum of digits = prime(n), or 0 if no such number exists.

A083185.name: Palindromic primes using only nonprime digits (0,1,4,6,8,9).

A083186.name: Sum of first n primes whose indices are primes.
formula: a(n) ~ (n log n)^2 / 2. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Oct 20 2015

A083188.name: Lexicographically earliest sequence of distinct primes with the property that for all n >= 1, the concatenation of a(n), a(n+1), ..., a(2n-1) is a prime.

A083190.name: a(1) = 1; for n>1 a(n) is smallest prime not occurring earlier such that the concatenation of a(n), a(n+1), ..., a(2n-1) is a composite number.

A083192.name: a(1) = 1, then the rearrangement of composite numbers such that the concatenation of n terms from the n-th term is a prime. (Concatenation of n-th term to (2n-1)th term is a prime number).

A083193.name: a(1) = 1 and then primes arising in A083192. Concatenation of n-th term to (2n-1)th term of A083192.

A083195.name: Multiples of n obtained as the concatenation of terms A075618(n) to A075618(2n-1).

A083197.name: Triangular array, read by rows, where if n is odd the n-th row consists of n least unused nonprimes, while if n is even the n-th row consists of the n least unused primes.

A083199.name: Exponent of largest power of 2 dividing A061419(n).

A083201.name: a(1) = 1. For n>1, let x = a(n-1)+1; then a(n) is the first prime in the sequence 2*x-1, 2*x-3, 4*x-1, 4*x-3, 8*x-1, 8*x-3, ..., (2^k)*x-1, (2^k)*x-3, ...

A083203.name: a(1) = 1, then smallest number not included earlier such that a(n)*a(n+1) + 1 is a cube.

A083204.name: Bases for the cubes arising in A083203.

A083205.name: a(1) = 1, then smallest number not included earlier such that a(n)*a(n+1) + 1 is an n-th power.

A083206.name: Number of subsets of divisors of n having equal sums as their complements.
formula: a(n) = if sigma(n) mod 2 = 1 then 0 else f(n,sigma(n)/2,2), where sigma=A000203 and f(n,m,k) = if k<=m then f(n,m,k+1)+f(n,m-k,k+1)*0^(n mod k) else 0^m, cf. A033630, also using f. [From _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 10 2010]

A083207.name: Zumkeller or integer-perfect numbers: numbers n whose divisors can be partitioned into two disjoint sets with equal sum.

A083209.name: Numbers with exactly one subset of their sets of divisors such that the complement has the same sum.

A083210.name: Numbers with no subset of their divisors such that the complement has the same sum.

A083211.name: Abundant numbers (A005101) with no subset of their divisors such that the complement has the same sum.

A083214.name: Numbers n for which 3 | p(n), where p(n) = A000041(n) is the n-th partition number.

A083216.name: Fibonacci-like sequence of composite numbers with a(0) = 20615674205555510, a(1) = 3794765361567513.

A083217.name: a(n) = (2*5^n+(-1)^n)/3.
formula: a(n) = sum{k=0..n, sum{j=0..n-k, C(n,j)C(n-j,k)J(n-j+1)}} where J(n)=A001045(n); - _Paul Barry_, May 19 2006
a(0)=1, a(n)=5*a(n-1)-2 if n is odd; a(n)=5*a(n)+2 if n is even. - _Vincenzo Librandi_, Nov 18 2010

A083218.name: a(n) = n mod (spf(n+1)+1), where spf(n) is the smallest prime factor of n (A020639).

A083219.name: a(n) = n - 2*floor(n/4).
formula: Bisection: a(2*k) = 2*floor((n+2)/4), a(2*k+1) = a(2*k) + 1, k >= 0. - _Wolfdieter Lang_, May 08 2017
E.g.f.: ((1 + x)*cosh(x) - cos(x) + (2 + x)*sinh(x) - sin(x))/2. - _Stefano Spezia_, May 27 2021

A083220.name: a(n) = n + (n mod 4).
formula: For n > 4, a(n) = a(n-4) + 4. - _Zak Seidov_, Feb 23 2017
E.g.f.: (1 + x)*cosh(x) - cos(x) + (2 + x)*sinh(x) - sin(x). - _Stefano Spezia_, May 28 2021

A083221.name: Sieve of Eratosthenes arranged as an array and read by antidiagonals as A(1,1), A(1,2), A(2,1), A(1,3), A(2,2), A(3,1), ...

A083230.name: Number of repunit divisors of n.

A083235.name: First differences of A063742, the possible values for cototients.

A083236.name: First order recursion: a(0)=2; a(n) = prime(n) - a(n-1).

A083237.name: First order recursion: a(0)=5; a(n)=prime(n)-a(n-1).
formula: Same implicit relationship: a(n-1)+a(n)=prime(n), the n-th prime;

A083238.name: First order recursion: a(0)=1; a(n) = sigma(1,n) - a(n-1).

A083240.name: Primes prime(j) such that prime(j)-j is a true power of prime.

A083243.name: Numbers n for which there are more divisors and coprimes than other numbers less than n: A045763(n) < A073757(n) or A045763(n)<n/2 or A073757(n)>n/2.

A083244.name: n is in the sequence iff number of numbers unrelated to n is larger than that of related ones[=divisors and coprimes] to n: A045763(n)>A073757(n) or A045763(n)>n/2 or A073757(n)<n/2.
formula: Numbers n such that n - d(n) - phi(n) + 1 > n/2.

A083245.name: Difference between numbers of related and numbers of unrelated numbers belonging to n: a(n) = A073757(n)-A045763(n) = (n-u(n))-u(n) = n-2*A045763(n) = 2*A073757(n)-n.

A083246.name: Numbers n such that at least one of the following four conditions is satisfied: 1# d(n)=phi(n); 2# d(n)=u(n); 3# phi(n)=u(n), or 4# n=2u(n). Here d(n)=A000005(n) is the number of divisors of n, phi(n)=A000010(n) is Euler's totient and u(n)=A045763(n) is the size of the 'unrelated set'.

A083247.name: Numbers satisfying the following inequalities: A000010(n)>A045763(n)>A000005(n).

A083248.name: Numbers satisfying the following inequalities: A045763[n]>A000010[n]>A000005[n].

A083249.name: Numbers n with A045763(n) = n + 1 - d(n) - phi(n) < d(n) < phi(n).

A083250.name: Numbers n for which abs(A045763(n) - A073757(n)) = 3, i.e., signed difference of size of related and unrelated sets to n equals either 3 or -3.

A083251.name: Numbers n such that abs(A045763(n) - A073757(n)) = 2, i.e., signed difference of size of related and unrelated sets to n equals either 2 or -2.
formula: a(n) = 8 * (A076274(n-1) + 1) for n > 3, as proved by Lawrence Sze. - _Ralf Stephan_, Nov 16 2004

A083252.name: Numbers n for which abs(A045763(n) - A073757(n)) = 5, i.e., signed difference of size of related and unrelated sets to n equals either 5 or -5.

A083253.name: Smallest number k for which abs(A045763(k) - A073757(k)) = n, i.e., signed difference of size of related and unrelated sets to k equals either n or -n.

A083255.name: Odd composite numbers k such that cototient(k) - phi(k) = k - 2*phi(k) is an odd prime.

A083259.name: a(n) = gcd(n, A071364(n)), where A071364(n) is the smallest number with same sequence of exponents in canonical prime factorization as n.

A083262.name: a(n) = sigma(A046523(n)), sum of divisors of the least number with the same prime signature as n.

A083263.name: Numbers k such that the difference of the largest and smallest prime factors of k divides k.

A083264.name: Numbers k such that the difference d of the largest and smallest prime factors of k is a composite divisor of k.
formula: Solutions to x mod d = 0 where d = A006530(x) - A020639(x) is composite.

A083266.name: Sum of related numbers (counted in A073757) belonging to n: a(n) = A000203(n) + A023896(n) - 1; related = {divisor-set, RRS}.

A083267.name: Product of related numbers (counted in A073757) belonging to n; related = {divisor-set, RRS}: a(n) = A007955(n)*A001783(n).

A083268.name: a(n) is the lcm of related numbers to n (counted in A073757): related = {divisor-set, RRS}.

A083269.name: a(n) = pi(A052180(n)) = A000720(A052180(n)); subscript of last prime used in Eratosthenes sieve by which all composites between n-th and (n+1)th primes were excluded.

A083273.name: a(n) is the quotient of lcm of first n consecutive prime differences and A001223[n], the n-th term of consecutive p-differences.

A083275.name: a(n) = smallest number not occurring earlier such that a(1)*a(2)*...*a(n) - 1 is prime.

A083276.name: Number of distinct chess positions after n plies including differences due to availability and possibility of castling and en passant captures.

A083279.name: Length of odd/even runs in A061419, where a(2n)=length of n-th run of even numbers in A061419 and a(2n-1)=length of n-th run of odd numbers.

A083280.name: Number of 2-generator non-Abelian groups of order n.

A083281.name: Decimal expansion of h = Product_{p prime}(sqrt(p(p-1))*log(1/(1-1/p))).

A083284.name: Numbers m such that m and m+2 are both brilliant numbers, where brilliant numbers are semiprimes whose prime factors have an equal number of decimal digits, or whose prime factors are equal.

A083285.name: Numbers n such that n and n+4 are both brilliant numbers (A078972).

A083286.name: Decimal expansion of K(3), a constant related to the Josephus problem.

A083287.name: Continued fraction expansion of K(3), a constant related to the Josephus problem.

A083288.name: Sigma unitary-sigma perfect numbers: numbers m which satisfy the following equation for some integer k: sigma(usigma(m)) = k*m where usigma(m) is sum of unitary divisors of m.

A083289.name: Least k such that 10^n+k is a brilliant number (cf. A078972).

A083290.name: Number of partitions of n into distinct parts which are coprime to n and which are also pairwise relatively prime.

A083291.name: Triangular array read by rows: T(n,k) = k*floor(n/10) + n mod 10, 0<=k<=n.

A083303.name: Let Pi= sum(k>=0, u(k)/k!) where u(k)>=0 are integer (u(k)=A075874(k)), then sequence gives values of m such that u(m)=0.

A083309.name: a(n) is the number of times that sums 3+-5+-7+-11+-...+-prime(2n+1) of the first 2n odd primes is zero. There are 2^(2n-1) choices for the sign patterns.

A083310.name: Least number greater than n that contains all the decimal digits of n.

A083311.name: Minimal number of edit-steps (insert, delete, substitute) to obtain in decimal representation the least number greater n that contains all digits of n (A083310).

A083312.name: Largest integer m such that 1+2+...+m divides n.

A083313.name: a(0)=1; a(n) = 3^n - 2^(n-1) for n >= 1.
formula: a(n) = A090888(n-1, 4), for n > 0. - _Ross La Haye_, Sep 21 2004

A083318.name: a(0) = 1; for n>0, a(n) = 2^n + 1.
formula: a(n) = Min{m: A008687(m) = n+1}. - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Jul 25 2006
Row sums of triangle A132749; = binomial transform of [1, 2, 0, 2, 0, 2, 0, 2,...]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Aug 28 2007

A083323.name: a(n) = 3^n - 2^n + 1.
formula: Row sums of triangle A134319. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Oct 19 2007

A083324.name: An alternating sum of decreasing powers.

A083329.name: a(0) = 1; for n > 0, a(n) = 3*2^(n-1) - 1.
formula: a(0) = 1, a(n) = sum of all previous terms + n. - _Amarnath Murthy_, Jun 20 2004
a(n) = A086893(n) + A061547(n+1), n > 0. - _Yosu Yurramendi_, Jan 16 2017

A083334.name: a(n) = 12*a(n-2) - 25*a(n-4).
formula: a(n) = (x^(n+1) + (-1)^(n+1)*(x-2)^(n+1))/2^ceiling(n/2 + 1) where x = 1 + sqrt(11). - _Ben Paul Thurston_, Aug 30 2006 [edited by _Jon E. Schoenfield_, Jun 25 2019]

A083337.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 2*a(n-2); a(0)=0, a(1)=3.
formula: a(n) = a(n-1) + 3*A026150(n-1). a(n)/A026150(n) converges to sqrt(3).
a(n) = lower left term of [1,1; 3,1]^n. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Mar 12 2008
a(n) = (1/2)*(1+sqrt(3))^n*sqrt(3) - (1/2)*sqrt(3)*(1-sqrt(3))^n, with n >= 0. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Jun 10 2008

A083338.name: Number of partitions of odd numbers into three primes and of even numbers into two primes.
formula: a(n) = if n is even then A045917(n/2) else A054860((n-1)/2).
For even n: a(n) = A061358(n); for odd n: a(n) = A068307(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 14 2017

A083339.name: a(n) is the number of distinct prime factors of n that occur in partitions into two primes when n is even and into three primes when n is odd.
formula: If n is even, a(n) = A010051(n/2), if n is an odd prime, a(n) = 0, and for odd composites (conjecturally), a(n) = A001221(n). - _Antti Karttunen_, Sep 14 2017

A083340.name: Numbers n such that A020549(n)=(n!)^2+1 is a semiprime.

A083341.name: Smaller factor of the n-th semiprime of the form (m!)^2+1.
formula: Numbers p such that p*q = (A083340(n)!)^2 + 1, p, q prime, p < q.

A083342.name: Decimal expansion of average deviation of the total number of prime factors.

A083343.name: Decimal expansion of constant B3 (or B_3) related to the Mertens constant.
formula: Equals lim_{x to infty} ( log x - sum_{p <= x} log p / p ). - Dick Boland, Mar 09 2008
Equals EulerGamma - Sum_{n >= 2} P'(n), where P'(n) is the prime zeta P function derivative. - _Jean-François Alcover_, Apr 25 2016
Equals lim_{n->oo} Sum_{k=1..n} mu(k)^2/phi(k) - log(n) (Ward, 1927). - _Amiram Eldar_, Mar 05 2021

A083344.name: a(n) = A082457(n) - A066715(n) = gcd(2n+1, A057643(2n+1)) - gcd(2n+1, A000203(2n+1)).
formula: a(n) = gcd(2n+1, lcm(1+D(2n+1))) - gcd(2n+1, sigma(2n+1)), gcd(2n+1, A057643(2n+1)) - gcd(2n+1, A000203(2n+1)), where D(x) is the set of divisors of x.

A083347.name: Numbers n such that Sum(e/p: n=Product(p^e)) < 1.

A083348.name: Numbers n such that r(n) = Sum(e/p: n=Product(p^e)) > 1.
formula: Numbers n such that n = n mod n', where n' is the arithmetic derivative of n. - _Paolo P. Lava_, Mar 20 2012

A083349.name: Least positive integers not appearing previously such that the self-convolution cube-root of this sequence consists entirely of integers.

A083350.name: Integer coefficients of a power series A(x) such that A(x)^3 = A083349(x).

A083351.name: Numbers n such that 5*7^n + 2 is prime.

A083352.name: Least positive integer coefficients of power series A(x) such that the coefficients of A(x)^2 + A(x) - 1 consist entirely of squares.

A083353.name: Coefficients of power series A(x) consist entirely of squares, where A(x) = A083352(x)^2 + A083352(x) - 1.

A083354.name: Square root of coefficients of power series: A083352(x)^2 + A083352(x) - 1; term-by-term square root of A083353.

A083355.name: Number of preferential arrangements for the set partitions of the n-set [1,2,3,...,n].
formula: Representation as a double infinite series (Dobinski-type formula), in Maple notation: a(n) = sum(k^n/k!*sum(p^k/(2*exp(1))^p, p=1..infinity), k=1..infinity)/2, n=1, 2... . - _Karol A. Penson_ and Pawel Blasiak (blasiak(AT)lptl.jussieu.fr), Nov 30 2003
a(n) ~ n!/(2 * c * (log c)^(n+1)) where c = 1 + log 2.
a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} C(n, k)*Bell(k)*a(n-k). - _Vladeta Jovovic_, Jul 24 2003
a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n} Sum_{j=1..i} j!*Stirling2(i,j)*Stirling2(n,i). - _Thomas Wieder_, May 09 2005
a(n) = Sum_{k >= 0} Bell(n,k)/2^(k+1), where Bell(n,x) = Sum_{k = 0..n} Stirling2(n,k)*x^k denotes the n-th Bell or exponential polynomial. - _Peter Bala_, Jul 09 2014

A083356.name: Total area of all incongruent integer-sided rectangles of area <= n.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{k=1..n} k*ceiling(d(k)/2), where d(k)=A000005(k) is the number of divisors of k.
G.f.: x*f'(x)/(1 - x), where f(x) = Sum_{k>=1} x^k^2/(1 - x^k). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 12 2017

A083357.name: Numbers n such that A083356(n) (the total area of all incongruent integer-sided rectangles of area <= n) is a square.

A083358.name: Square root of n-th perfect square in A083356.

A083359.name: Visible Factor Numbers, or VFNs: numbers n with the property that every prime factor of n can be found in the decimal expansion of n and every digit of n can be found in a prime factor.

A083360.name: Subsequence of sequence A083359 in which factors do not overlap in the number.

A083361.name: Subsequence of sequence A083359 in which every prime factor can be found in the number at least as often as it is factor of the number.

A083362.name: Square table, read by antidiagonals, of least distinct positive integers such that the sum of any two consecutive terms in any row is a square number.

A083365.name: Expansion of psi(x) / phi(x) in powers of x where phi(), psi() are Ramanujan theta functions.
formula: Expansion of f(-x^4) / f(x) = psi(x) / phi(x) = psi(x^2) / psi(x) = psi(-x) / phi(-x^2) = 1 / (chi(x) * chi(-x^2)) = 1 / (chi^2(x) * chi(-x)) = chi(-x) / chi^2(-x^2) = (psi(x^2) / phi(x))^(1/2) in powers of x where phi(), psi(), chi(), f() are Ramanujan theta functions.
Expansion of k^(1/4) / (2^(1/2) * q^(1/8)) in powers of q where k is elliptic modulus and q is the nome.
Expansion of q^(-1/8) * eta(q) * eta(q^4)^2 / eta(q^2)^3 in powers of q.
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = q * A(q^8) satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2)) where f(u, v) = v^2 - u^4 * (1 + 4*v^4).
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = q * A(q^8) satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^3)) where f(u, v) = v^4 - u^4 + u*v + 4*(u*v)^3.
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = q * A(q^8) satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2), B(q^4)) where f(u, v, w) = w - u^2*v*(1 + 2*w^2). - _Michael Somos_, May 29 2005
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = q * A(q^8) satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^2), B(q^3), B(q^6)) where f(u1, u2, u3, u6) = u2*u6 - u1*u3 * (u2^2 + u6^2). - _Michael Somos_, May 29 2005
Given g.f. A(x), then B(q) = sqrt(2) * q * A(q^8) satisfies 0 = f(B(q), B(q^7)) where f(u, v) = (1 - u^8) * (1 - v^8) - (1 - u*v)^8. - _Michael Somos_, Jan 01 2006
G.f. is a period 1 Fourier series which satisfies f(-1 / (32 t)) = 2^(-1/2) * g(t) where q = exp(2 Pi i t) and g() is the g.f. for A108494. - _Michael Somos_, Feb 29 2012
G.f.: (1+1/Q(0))/2, where Q(k)= 1 + x^(k+1) + x^(k+1)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Apr 30 2013
G.f.: (-x^2; x^2)_{-1/2} = ((-1; x^2)_{1/2})/2, where (a; q)_n is the q-Pochhammer symbol. - _Vladimir Reshetnikov_, Nov 20 2016
a(0) = 1, a(n) = -(1/n)*Sum_{k=1..n} A109506(k)*a(n-k) for n > 0. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Apr 14 2017

A083366.name: Numbers n such that 7*11^n + 2 is prime.

A083367.name: n is equal to the sum of its divisors after the digits of each divisor have been sorted in ascending order.

A083368.name: A Fibbinary system represents a number as a sum of distinct Fibonacci numbers (instead of distinct powers of two). Using representations without adjacent zeros, a(n) = the highest bit-position which changes going from n-1 to n.
formula: a(n) = a(k)+1 if n = ceiling(phi*k) where phi is the golden ratio; otherwise a(n) = 1. - _Tom Edgar_, Aug 25 2015

A083370.name: Primes satisfying f(2p)=p when f(1)=5 (see comment).

A083371.name: Primes satisfying f(2*p)=p when f(1)=7 (see comment).

A083372.name: Least number having exactly two odd prime factors that differ by 2n.

A083373.name: 2n is equal to the sum of its divisors after the digits have been sorted in descending order (zeros dropped).

A083374.name: a(n) = n^2 * (n^2 - 1)/2.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{i=1..n^2-1} i. - _Wesley Ivan Hurt_, Nov 24 2015

A083376.name: Numbers n such that A053664(n) is prime.

A083377.name: a(n) = the largest integer whose square has n digits and first digit 1.

A083378.name: a(n) is the largest integer whose cube has n digits and first digit 1, except that a(2)=2.

A083379.name: a(n) = the number of squares with at most n digits and first digit 1.

A083380.name: a(n) is the number of cubes with at most n digits and first digit 1.

A083381.name: Square array giving the number of trellis edges T(i,j) (i >= 0, j >= 0), read by antidiagonals.
formula: Recurrence: T(i, 0) = i, T(0, j) = j, and T(i, j) = T(i-1, j) + T(i, j-1) - T(i-1, j-1) + 3 for i, j >= 1.

A083382.name: Write the numbers from 1 to n^2 consecutively in n rows of length n; a(n) = minimal number of primes in a row.

A083385.name: Total height of all elements in all preferential arrangements of n elements, where elements at the bottom level have height 1.

A083386.name: Number (undirected) Hamiltonian paths in the 5 X n knight graph.

A083387.name: Numbers n such that the number formed by the digits of 2n sorted in ascending order is equal to the sum of the divisors of n after the digits of each divisor have been sorted in ascending order.

A083388.name: a(n) = beginning of a run of at least n primes when x -> 3*x + 2 is iterated.

A083389.name: Numbers n such that the number formed by the digits of 2n sorted in descending order is equal to the sum of the divisors of n after the digits of each divisor have been sorted in descending order (all zeros dropped).

A083391.name: n-th Payam number E_{-}(n), defined as the smallest positive odd integer k such that for every positive integer n, the number k*2^n-1 is not divisible by any primes p such that the multiplicative order of 2 mod p is less than or equal to e.

A083392.name: Alternating partial sums of A000217.

formula: G.f.: g(x) = 1/(1-x) + (1/(1-x)^2)*Sum_{j>=0} x^2^j. - _Hieronymus Fischer_, Jun 12 2012; corrected by _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Jan 08 2017

A083653.name: Consider the binary Champernowne sequence (A030190): smallest number m such that in binary representation n is contained in the concatenation of m and its successors.

A083654.name: Consider the binary Champernowne sequence (A030190): number of successive numbers to be concatenated beginning with A083653(n) such that in binary representation n is contained.

A083655.name: Numbers which do not appear prematurely in the binary Champernowne word (A030190).

A083659.name: Denominator of fraction equal to the continued fraction [p(n); p(n-1),...,5,3,2].

A083660.name: Smallest nonnegative integer m such that the concatenation of the integers from n to 1 interspersed with those of m, in base 10, is prime.

A083662.name: a(n) = a(floor(n/2)) + a(floor(n/4)), n > 0; a(0)=1.
formula: For n > 0, a(n) = F([log(n)/log(2)]+3) where F(k) denotes the k-th Fibonacci number. For n >= 3, F(n) appears 2^(n-3) times. More generally, if p is an integer > 1 and a(n) = a(floor(n/p)) + a(floor(n/p^2)), n > 0, a(0)=1, then for n > 0, a(n) = F(floor(log(n)/log(p)) + 3).

A083663.name: Least k such that k*n!-1 is prime.

A083664.name: a(1) = 1, a(n) = if n mod 10 = 0 then n else smallest number m, not occurring earlier such that m*a(n-d) is a palindrome, where d = if n mod 10 = 1 then 2 else 1.

A083667.name: Number of antisymmetric binary relations on a set of n labeled points.

A083668.name: Prime indices of prime Fibonacci numbers.

A083669.name: Number of ordered quintuples (a,b,c,d,e), -n <= a,b,c,d,e <= n, such that a+b+c+d+e = 0.

A083670.name: Number of different antisymmetric relations on n unlabeled points.
formula: Euler transform of A101460. - _Andrew Howroyd_, Oct 24 2019

A083671.name: Array read by rows in which each row describes in words the composition of the previous row.

A083674.name: Triangular numbers whose sum of divisors is also a triangular number.

A083675.name: Triangular numbers whose sum of aliquot divisors is also a triangular number.

A083676.name: Triangular numbers whose sum of aliquot divisors is a prime number.

A083677.name: Define f(n, k) to be the concatenation of the first n primes, with n-1 k's inserted between the primes. Then a(n) is the smallest k >= 0 such that f(n, k) is prime, or -1 if no such prime exists.

A083678.name: Numbers n = d_1 d_2 ... d_k (in base 10) with properties that k is even and d_i + d_{k+1-i} = 10 for all i.

A083679.name: Decimal expansion of log(4/3).
formula: Limit of a special sum: log(4/3) = Sum_{k>=1} (Sum_{i=1..k} 1/(i*2^i))/2^(k+1).

A083682.name: Sum of aliquot divisors of semiprimes.

A083684.name: Numbers k such that there is no nonnegative integer m such that m < k*prime(k) and the concatenated decimal number fp(k,m) = prime(1).m.prime(2).m. ... .prime(k-1).m.prime(k) is prime.

A083685.name: a(n) is the smallest prime of the form k*lcm(1..n) - 1.

A083687.name: Numerator of B(2n)*H(2n)/n*(-1)^(n+1) where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number and H(k) the k-th harmonic number.
formula: Miki's identity : B(n)*H(n)*(2/n) = sum(i=2, n-2, B(i)/i*B(n-i)/(n-i)*(1-C(n, i)))

A083688.name: Denominator of B(2n)*H(2n)/n where B(k) is the k-th Bernoulli number and H(k) the k-th harmonic number.
formula: Miki's identity : B(n)*H(n)*(2/n) = sum(i=2, n-2, B(i)/i*B(n-i)/(n-i)*(1-C(n, i)))

A083689.name: Numbers n such that the sum of the factorials of the digits of n! is prime.

A083690.name: a(n) = number of partitions of n wherein the sum of the 1's is no more than the sum of the other parts.

A083691.name: Length of list generated by n replacements of k by {-1-|k|, ..., 1+|k|} with increment 2, starting with {0}.

A083692.name: Length of list generated by n replacements of k by {-1-|k|, .., 1+|k|} with increment 2, starting with {1}.
formula: Drop first 2 terms from A083691 and divide by 2.

A083693.name: Sum of absolute values of list generated by n replacements of k by {-1-|k|, .., 1+|k|} with increment 2, starting with {1}.

A083695.name: a(n) = 2*a(n-1) + 5*a(n-2).
formula: G.f.: 1/Q(0) -1, where Q(k) = 1 + 5*x^2 - (3*k+4)*x + x*(3*k+1 - 5*x)/Q(k+1); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Oct 07 2013

A083698.name: Partial quotients of the continued fraction which has convergents with the least possible prime denominators (A072999).

A083699.name: Numerators of the continued fraction convergents which have the least possible prime denominators (A072999).

A083700.name: Decimal expansion of the limit of the n-th continued fraction convergent, A083699(n)/A072999(n), which has the least prime denominator.

A083701.name: Smallest prime having Fibonacci(n) as least primitive root, or 0 if no such prime exists.

A083702.name: Smallest number having Fibonacci(n) as least primitive root, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083703.name: Expansion of eta(q)^4/eta(q^4) in powers of q.
formula: a(0) = 1, a(n) = -(4/n)*Sum_{k=1..n} A285895(k)*a(n-k) for n > 0. - _Seiichi Manyama_, Apr 29 2017

A083706.name: a(n) = 2^(n+1)+n-1.
formula: Row sums of A130301. - _Gary W. Adamson_, May 20 2007

A083710.name: Number of integer partitions of n with a part dividing all the other parts.
formula: Equals left border of triangle A137587 starting (1, 2, 3, 5, 6, 11,...). - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jan 27 2008
Comment from Joerg Arndt, Jun 08 2009: Sequence has g.f. 1 + Sum_{n>=1} x^n/eta(x^n). The g.f. for partitions into parts that are a multiple of n is x^n/eta(x^n), now sum over n.

_Gary W. Adamson_'s comment is equivalent to the formula a(n) = Sum_{d|n} p(d-1) where p(i) = number of partitions of i (A000041(i)). Hence A083710 has g.f. Sum_{d>=1} p(d-1)*x^d/(1-x^d), - _N. J. A. Sloane_, Jun 08 2009

A083714.name: (greatest prime <= n) - (greatest prime factor of n).

A083715.name: (greatest prime <= n) mod (greatest prime factor of n).

A083716.name: a(n) = integer part of (greatest prime <= n)/(greatest prime factor of n); a(1) = 1.

A083717.name: (Greatest prime <= n) * (greatest prime factor of n).

A083718.name: (greatest prime <= n) + (greatest prime factor of n).

A083719.name: a(n) = n * [1 + sum(k=1 to n-1) prime(k)].

A083720.name: Product of primes less than greatest prime factor of n but not dividing n.

A083721.name: Number of primes greater than the greatest prime factor of n but not greater than n.

A083722.name: Product of primes greater than the greatest prime factor of n but not greater than n.

A083724.name: Numbers k such that 11*7^k + 2 is prime.

A083725.name: a(n) = n * [1 + sum(k=1 to n) prime(k)].

A083729.name: Decimal expansion of sqrt(2)/(sqrt(2)-1)^2 = 3*sqrt(2)+4.
formula: Equals A010474 plus 4. - _R. J. Mathar_, Sep 17 2008

A083730.name: Greatest prime^2 factor of n, or a(n)=1 for squarefree n.

A083731.name: Triangular array such that partial sums define A008284.

A083732.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 2 and 5.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 2^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 5^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083733.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 2 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 2^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083734.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 3 and 5.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 3^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 5^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083735.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 3 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 3^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083736.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 2,5 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 2^(k-1) = 1 (mod k), 5^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083738.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 2,3 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 2^(k-1) = 1 (mod k), 3^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).

A083739.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 2, 3, 5 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 2^(k-1) = 1 (mod k), 3^(k-1) = 1 (mod k), 5^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k)
A005938 INTERSECT A083737. - _R. J. Mathar_, Feb 07 2008

A083740.name: Pseudoprimes to bases 3,5 and 7.
formula: a(n) = n-th positive integer k(>1) such that 3^(k-1) = 1 (mod k), 5^(k-1) = 1 (mod k) and 7^(k-1) = 1 (mod k).
Intersection of A083734 and A005938. Intersection of A083735 and A005936. - _R. J. Mathar_, Apr 05 2011

A083741.name: a(n) = l(n) + a(l(n)), where l(n) = n - 2^floor(log2(n)) (A053645).

A083743.name: a(1) = 1; if a(n-1) + n is prime then a(n) = a(n-1) + n, else a(n) = a(n-1).

A083744.name: a(1) = 1; if a(n-1) + n is composite then a(n) = a(n-1) + n, else a(n) = a(n-1).

A083745.name: a(1) = 1; if a(n-1) + n is composite or 1 then a(n) = a(n-1) + n, else a(n) = a(n-1) - n.

A083746.name: a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2; for n>2, a(n) = 3*(n-2)*(n-2)!.
formula: Sum_{k=1..n} a(k) = A052560(n-1); for n>2: a(n) = A052673(n-2). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Apr 14 2007

A083747.name: Smallest number m such that n followed by m ones yields a prime; a(p) = 0 because 0 ones are necessary to yield a prime.

A083748.name: Star numbers (A003154) whose digital sum and product of nonzero digits are both triangular numbers.

A083749.name: Brilliant star numbers: semiprimes of the form 6n^2 - 6n + 1 such that both prime factors have the same number of decimal digits.

A083750.name: Numbers n such that 2111131111...p(n-1)1111p(n) is prime.

A083751.name: Number of partitions of n into >= 2 parts and with minimum part >= 2.

A083752.name: Minimal k > n such that (4k+3n)(4n+3k) is a square.
formula: n < a(n) <= 393n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 13 2013

A083753.name: Smallest palindromic number with exactly n divisors, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083754.name: a(1) = 1 and then smallest odd number not occurring earlier such that the concatenation a(1)a(2)a(3)... is a prime.

A083756.name: Beginning with 5, rearrangement of odd primes such that every concatenation beginning with the first term is a prime.

A083758.name: Lexicographically earliest infinite sequence of distinct primes such that the concatenation of the initial n terms is a prime for all n >= 1.

A083760.name: Rearrangement of even numbers such that concatenation of terms beginning with the first with a 1 as the least significant digit is a prime.

A083762.name: Rearrangement of natural numbers such that concatenation of terms beginning with the first one with a 1 as the least significant digit is a prime.

A083764.name: n-th row of the following triangle contains n palindromic multiples of n beginning with n. Sequence contains the triangle by rows.

A083767.name: Sum of n-th row of A083764 divided by n.

A083768.name: Triangle formed by dividing row n of A083764 by n.

A083769.name: a(1)=2; for n >= 2, a(n) = smallest even number such that a(1)*a(2)*...*a(n) + 1 is prime.

A083771.name: Rearrangement of primes such that every partial product + 1 is a prime.

A083773.name: The n-th row of the following triangle contains n distinct numbers such that the product of (n-1) of them + 1 is always a prime. The first (n-1) numbers are the smallest set whose product +1 is a prime and the n-th term is chosen to satisfy the requirement. a(1) = 1 by convention. Sequence contains the triangle by rows.

A083775.name: Triangle of primes associated with A083773.

A083776.name: The n-th row of the following triangle contains n distinct primes such that the product of (n-1) of them + 2 is prime in all cases. The first (n-1) numbers are the smallest set whose product +2 is a prime and the n-th term is chosen to satisfy the requirement. a(1) = 2 by convention. Sequence contains the triangle by rows.

A083778.name: Triangle of primes derived in A083776.

A083779.name: n-th row of the following triangle contains n even numbers such that every sum of n-1 of them + 1 is a prime. Sequence contains the triangle by rows.

A083781.name: Triangle of primes associated with A083779.

A083782.name: n-th row of the following triangle contains n distinct natural numbers such that every sum of n-1 of them +1 is a prime,n >1, with a(1) = 1 by convention. Sequence contains the triangle by rows.

A083784.name: Triangle of primes derived from A083782.

A083785.name: Triangle read by rows in which the n-th row gives the smallest set of n consecutive numbers with the same prime signatures.

A083787.name: Sequence contains the prime signature pertaining to the n-th row of A083785.

A083788.name: Triangle read by rows, in which n-th row contains smallest set of n consecutive numbers with distinct prime signatures.

A083792.name: Lexicographically first increasing sequence such that no two successive terms have the same prime signature.

A083793.name: Numbers n such that n and n-1 have the same prime signature. Numbers not included in A083792.

A083794.name: Numbers n such that tau(n) is different from tau(n-1), where tau(m) = number of divisors of m.
formula: Erdős proved that a(n) ~ n. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, Dec 05 2012

A083795.name: Numbers n such that n and n-1 have the same number of divisors. Numbers not included in A083794.

A083796.name: Triangle read by rows in which the n-th row contains n lexicographically earliest distinct numbers such that the sum of the (n-1) terms other than the r-th term is divisible by r.

A083798.name: Triangle obtained by replacing each term in A083796 with the sum of all other terms in that row.

A083801.name: Triangle read by rows obtained by replacing each term T(n,k) in A083796 with the sum, divided by r, of the other n-1 terms in the n-th row.

A083803.name: Smallest number k such that the concatenations k 2n-1 and 2n-1 k are both primes, or 0 if n = 5m+3.

A083804.name: a(1) = 1. If the (n-1)th partial concatenation is divisible by n then a(n) = 0. Otherwise, a(n) is the smallest positive number such that the n-th partial concatenation is divisible by n.

A083805.name: n-th partial concatenation of terms of A083804 divided by n.

A083806.name: Perfect powers using only prime digits and 1.

A083807.name: Perfect powers using only composite digits 4,6,8,9 and 0.

A083808.name: Smallest prime == 1 (mod n-th unary number U(n) = (10^n-1)/9).

A083809.name: Let f(n) be the smallest prime == 1 mod n (cf. A034694). Sequence gives triangle T(j,k) = f^k(j) for 1 <= k <= j, read by rows.

A083810.name: a(n) = f^(n) (n), where f(n) is the smallest prime == 1 mod n (cf. A034694).

A083811.name: Numbers n such that 2n+1 is the digit reversal of n+1.

A083812.name: 4n-1 is the digit reversal of n-1.

A083815.name: Semiprimes whose prime factors are distinct and the reversal of one factor is equal to the other.

A083818.name: Numbers n such that 2n-1 is the digit reversal of n.

A083819.name: a(1) = 1, then the smallest k > 1 such that nk + 1 is the digit reversal of k + 1, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083820.name: Primes in which odd positioned digits are prime and even positioned digits are composite. The least significant digit is taken to be the first digit.

A083821.name: Primes in which odd positioned digits are composite and even positioned digits are primes. The least significant digit is the taken to be the first digit.

A083822.name: a(n) = digit reversal of 3*n, divided by 3.

A083823.name: a(1) = 15; then numbers obtained at every stage of division by 3 in the following process: multiply by 3, reverse the digits, divide by 3, reverse the digits, multiply by 3, reverse the digit, divide by 3.

A083824.name: a(n) = digit reversal of 9*n, divided by 9.

A083825.name: a(1) = 12; then numbers obtained at every stage of division by 9 in the following process. multiply by 9, reverse the digits, divide by 9, reverse the digits, multiply by 9, reverse the digit, divide by 9, ...

A083826.name: Smallest k such that k+ 9*(A000042(n-1)*{n, mod 10) is digit reversal of k. A000042(n) = (10^n-1)/9.,a(10n) = 0.

A083827.name: Let x(n) = 123...n, y(n) = n...321; a(n) = y(n) concatenated with x(n) - x(n) concatenated with y(n).

A083828.name: Let x(n) = 123...n, y(n) = n...321; c(n) = delete the LSD of y(n) and concatenated with x(n); d(n) = delete LSD of x(n) and concatenate with y(n). a(n) = c(n) - d(n).

A083829.name: Palindromes n such that 3n + 1 is also a palindrome.

A083830.name: Palindromes of the form 3n + 1 where n is also a palindrome: palindromes arising in A083829.

A083831.name: Palindromes n such that 4n + 1 is also a palindrome.

A083832.name: Palindromes of the form 4n + 1 where n is also a palindrome. Palindromes arising in A083831.

A083833.name: Palindromes p such that 5p + 1 is also a palindrome.

A083834.name: Palindromes of the form 5p + 1 where p is also a palindrome. Palindromes arising in A083833.

A083835.name: Palindromes n such that 6n + 1 is also a palindrome.

A083836.name: Palindromes of the form 6n + 1 where n is also a palindrome. palindromes arising in A083835.

A083837.name: Smallest palindrome n such that kn + 1 is a palindrome, or 0 if no such number exists.

A083838.name: Smallest palindrome of the form nk+1 where k is also a palindrome:, or 0 if no such number exists; palindromes arising in A083837.

A083840.name: Palindromic primes which are a member of a twin prime pair.

A083841.name: Palindromic primes p such that p+2 is also a prime: members of A083840 which are the smaller member of a twin prime pair.

A083842.name: Palindromic primes p such that p-2 is also a prime: members of A083840 which are the larger member of a twin prime pair.

A083843.name: Total number of distinct cycles in a particular cellular automata of size n.

A083844.name: Number of primes of the form x^2 + 1 < 10^n.

A083845.name: a(n)^2 + 1 is largest prime of the form x^2 + 1 <= 10^n.

A083846.name: a(n) is the largest prime of the form x^2 + 1 <= 10^n.

A083847.name: a(n) = number of primes of the form x^2 + 1 <= 2^n.

A083848.name: a(n)^2 + 1 is largest prime of the form x^2 + 1 <= 2^n.

A083849.name: a(n) is the largest prime of the form x^2 + 1 <= 2^n.

A083850.name: Exponent of highest power of 11 dividing the n-th decimal palindrome; a(0) = 1.

A083851.name: Decimal palindromes that are not multiples of 11.

A083852.name: Decimal palindromes that are multiples of 11.

A083853.name: Smallest nonnegative integer that can be written as a sum of Fibonacci numbers in n ways, counting 1 twice as Fibonacci number.

A083854.name: Numbers that are squares, twice squares, three times squares, or six times squares, i.e., numbers whose squarefree part divides 6.
formula: a(n) is bounded below by 0.137918...*n^2 where 0.137918... = 3*(3-2*sqrt(2))*(2-sqrt(3)); the error appears to be O(n).

A083855.name: Multiplicands in the list of numbers which are squares, twice squares, three times squares, or six times squares (A083854).

A083856.name: Square array T(n,k) of generalized Fibonacci numbers, read by antidiagonals upwards (n, k >= 0).
formula: T(n, k) = (((1 + sqrt(4*n + 1))/2)^k - ((1 - sqrt(4*n + 1))/2)^k)/sqrt(4*n + 1). [corrected by _Michel Marcus_, Jun 25 2018]
The g.f. for row n >= 0 is x/(1 - x - n*x^2).
The g.f. for column k >= 1 is g(k,x) = 1/(1-x) + Sum_{m = 1..floor((k-1)/2)} (1 - x)^(-1 - m) * binomial(k - 1 - m, m) * Sum_{i = 0..m} x^i * Sum_{j = 0..i} (-1)^j * (i - j)^m * binomial(1 + m, j).

The g.f. for column k >= 1 is also g(k,x) = 1 + Sum_{m = 1..floor((k+1)/2)} ((1 - x)^(-m) * binomial(k-m, m-1) * Sum_{j = 0..m} (-1)^j * binomial(m, j) *  x^m * Phi(x, -m+1, -j+m)) + Sum_{s = 0..floor((k-1)/2)} binomial(k-s-1, s) * PolyLog(-s, x), where Phi is the Lerch transcendent function. (End)
T(n,k) = Sum_{i = 0..k} (-1)^(k+i) * binomial(k,i) * A083857(n,i). - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Dec 24 2019

A083857.name: Square array T(n,k) of binomial transforms of generalized Fibonacci numbers, read by ascending antidiagonals, with n, k >= 0.

A083858.name: Expansion of x/(1 - 3*x - 6*x^2).
formula: G.f.: Q(0)*x/2, where Q(k) = 1 + 1/(1 - x*(6*k+3 + 6*x )/( x*(6*k+6 + 6*x ) + 1/Q(k+1) )); (continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Sep 21 2013

a(n) = B(n, k + 2^(n-1)) - B(n,k) where B(n,k) is formed by the family of recursions b(n) = 3*(b(n-1) + b(n-2))/2, with b(0) = 1 and b(1) = k, as explained further in A249861. - _Richard R. Forberg_, Nov 04 2014

A083859.name: Main diagonal of generalized Fibonacci array A083856.
formula: a(n) = A193376(n-1,n) for n >= 2. - _R. J. Mathar_, Aug 23 2011
a(n) = y(n,n), where y(m+2,n) = y(m+1,n) + n*y(m,n) with y(0,n) = 0 and y(1,n) = 1 for all n. - _Benedict W. J. Irwin_, Nov 03 2016
a(n) = [x^n] x/(1 - x - n*x^2). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Oct 10 2017
a(n) = Sum_{s = 0..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(n-1-s, s) * n^s. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Dec 24 2019

A083860.name: First subdiagonal of generalized Fibonacci array A083856.
formula: a(n) = Sum_{s = 0..floor((n-1)/2)} binomial(n-1-s, s) * (n+1)^s. - _Petros Hadjicostas_, Dec 25 2019

A083861.name: Square array T(n,k) of second binomial transforms of generalized Fibonacci numbers, read by ascending antidiagonals, with n, k >= 0.
formula: O.g.f. for row n >= 0: -x/(-1 + 5*x + (n-6)*x^2) . - _R. J. Mathar_, Dec 02 2007
T(n,k) = 5*T(n,k-1) + (n - 6)*T(n,k-2) for k >= 2 with T(n,0) = 0 and T(n,1) = 1 for all n >= 0.
T(n,k) = Sum_{i = 0..k} Sum_{j = 0..i} binomial(k,i) * binomial(i,j) * A083856(n,j). (End)

A083863.name: Consider recurrence b(0) = n/3, b(n) = b(n-1)*floor(b(n-1)); sequence gives first integer reached, or -1 if no integer is ever reached.

A083865.name: Sums of (one or more distinct) k-perfect numbers.
formula: Empirical observation: a(n) = 2*n + Sum_{k >= 1} 4^k*floor(2*n/2^k) for 1 <= n <= 15 and 32 <= n <= 47; a(n) = 2*n - 1344 + Sum_{k >= 1} 4^k*floor(2*n/2^k) for 16 <= n <= 31. Note 1344 = 4^3 + 4^4 + 4^5. Cf. A000695. - _Peter Bala_, Nov 29 2016

If b(n) = 2*n + Sum_{k >= 1} 4^k*floor(2*n/2^k) - a(n), we also have b(n) = 1344 for 48 <= n <= 63, then 2400 for 64 <= n <= 79, 3744 for 80 <= n <= 95, 8008 for 96 <= n <= 111, etc.  The first case where b(n) is not constant on an interval 16*k <= n <= 16*k+15 is k=57214, where b(915431)=2747770287196 but b(915432)=2747770287312. - _Robert Israel_, Nov 29 2016

formula: a(n) = right and left terms in M^n * [1 1 1] where M = the 3X3 matrix [1 1 1 / 1 4 1 / 1 1 1]. M^n * [1 1 1] = [a(n) A030192(n) a(n)]. E.g. a(3) = 54 since M^3 * [1 1 1] = [54 144 54] = [a(3) A030192(3) a(3)]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Dec 18 2004
G.f.: A(x) = G(0) where G(k) =  1 + 3*x/((1-3*x) - x*(1-3*x)/(x + (1-3*x)/G(k+1) )); (recursively defined continued fraction). - _Sergei N. Gladkovskii_, Dec 29 2012.
